Code to read data

  1. Download data (gzip file), decompress gzip file, and split into 30 small json files
#!/bin/bash

wget http://snap.stanford.edu/data/amazon/productGraph/user_dedup.json.gz

gzip -d user_dedup.json.gz

awk 'NR%2789333==1{x="J"++i".json";}{print > x}' user_dedup.json
  1. Read json file using R into dataframe (Example below show how we do this step for J1.json)
library(jsonlite)

raw <- readLines("J1.json")

# add missing comma after }
n <- length(raw)
raw[-n] <- gsub("}", "},", raw[-n])
# add brakets at the beginning and end
raw <- c("[", raw, "]")

table <- fromJSON(raw, simplifyVector  = F)
df <- as.data.frame(do.call(rbind, table))
df2 <- apply(df,2,as.character)
df<- data.frame(df2)

head(df)

Output:

First 5 rows of dataframe from J1.json

Descriptions of variables

reviewerID - ID of the reviewer, e.g. A2SUAM1J3GNN3B

asin - ID of the product, e.g. 0000013714

reviewerName - name of the reviewer

helpful - helpfulness rating of the review, e.g. ⅔

reviewText - text of the review

overall - rating of the product

summary - summary of the review

unixReviewTime - time of the review (unix time)

reviewTime - time of the review (raw)

Statistical method

We plan to implement Natural language processing and sentiment analysis on the review data to predict the overall rating of the product.

  • Split data into testing and training set.
  • Tokenize each word of the review and categorize ratings of 1 or 2 as 0, and 5 as 1
  • Use TF-IDF to give weight to each word in the review, giving high scores to words that are common in a specific review but uncommon in all reviews.
  • Apply naive bayes and decision lists to distinguish positive and negative comments of the product, including reviewText and summary.
  • Perform linear regression to distinguish the features that are most accurate in terms of predicting the overall rating.
  • Establish the model according to the best parameter and compare it to the testing set.

Computational steps

  • First we will download the dataset and break it down into 18 .json files (each file is about 3GB)
  • Use CHTC to work on the 18 parallel jobs. For each job, we will perform the following procedures:
  1. Convert .json file into csv files
  2. Select asin, reviewText, overall column for future computation and drop others
  3. Split the files into training data and testing data and
  4. Break down the reviews into tokens, each containing one word
  5. Count the occurrence of each words and assign a score for each word based on its frequency in reviews and positive/negativeness
  6. Generate a model with the statistical methods discussed above using the training data and test the accuracy using the testing data
  7. Weight each parallel job based on the accuracy and combine the result of these jobs to get the final model
